 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003030><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub7.ezboard.com/uyonderwendobrayxe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yonder Wendobrayxe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Stalker of Wolves</span><br>  Posts: 213<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/7/01 6:58:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub7.ezboard.com/faegiswolvesfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> I was recently reborn as a bard (Patricio), and I'm in my mid 30's now.  I can't really be part of your tests, but I can suggest some things from observation being a bard and from experience listening to tanks complain and overanalyze everything for 51 levels before that.<br>
<br>
Firstly, haste is one of the best things you can do to a tank.  10% doesn't sound like much but among 3 (or 4 if you choose to melee) members of a party, it adds up nicely.  You have a monk and a rogue, 2 classes that base a lot on being able to dish a lot of melee damage in a short time.  Giving them each 10% haste as well as giving the shadowknight 10% (and again, maybe yourself if you melee) is probably equivalent to having another half a warrior in there swinging away.<br>
<br>
AoE = Agro on Everything.  The only times I can see using this is when there are only one or two targets to AoE and no chance of wanderers.  If you get agro stuff starts hitting you, and bashing you, and stunning you.  There's a saying I heard somewhere &quot;a stunned bard is nothing more than a bad tank.&quot;  Maybe I'm just a little paranoid, but the only AoE I have ever used is mez, which was very much worth it.<br>
<br>
That said, I love the 18% slow + snare spell.  Your tanks are hasted to hit at 110% while the creature is only hitting at 82% and furthermore can't run away.  The thing you have to take into account here is that this spell is resisted a ton (same with other slow spell).  On some mobs it sticks most of the time, but other ones it's resisted 50% or more.  Without another person who can slow in my group I consider this to be the one spell that should always be on what we fight, so those resists mean that I can only twist 2 songs and not 3, because I can't count on it taking hold on the first try.  Another reason you want to have it up is that if you start snaring your group generally expects creatures to be snared.  It's a Bad Thing (TM) to have creatures unexpectedly not snared.<br>
<br>
For a tank the best stats/effects he or she can have are as follows in order: regeneration, haste, AC, HPs, everything else.  Hence you know my answer to the third.  Every tick you heal you are decreasing downtime after the fight, and increasing durability during the fight (if the fight lasts only 10 ticks it's as if you've given all your tanks 100 extra hps).  In my experience the regen spell hasn't been too much of a taunt problem.  With an SK and a monk there shouldn't be a huge agro problem, and if it starts to be, just wait a few ticks before you start twisting it, let the tank build up some agro first.<br>
<br>
Having song damage output or buffing/debuffing a little AC cannot nearly make up for the sacrifice of one of these three things IMHO.<br>
<br>
So, special situations aside, I would say the answer is hands down (and supported by several people I asked) to twist slow/snare, regen, and haste, with slow/snare taking highest importance.  If you have an enchanter in the group, he/she can slow and haste better than you, so 1 tick regen, 2 ticks manasong, or perhaps 1 tick snare/slow depending if you need the mobs slowed.  Never underestimate the power of manasong.<br>
<br>
Now as for your question of stepping back and being turbo-buffer, except for special circumstances (like if the tanks are taking a huge beating and you need stringed for aoe mez and regen), I think it is best to get in the fray.  The new melee upgrade means that you supposedly can dish out more than half as melee damage as a warrior your level.  Why twist dots that would have equivalent damage output to your melee when you can just step in and melee and free up that extra song in your twist?  Only one of the songs above improves with an instrument, and that is regen, though you can use the instrument freely during downtime hit point recovery.  The key to remember is something you have already discovered: you are not a tank.  Taking melee damage and dishing it out are two different things.  You can dish it out fairly well, but you can't take it and be effective at twisting/living.  With proper agro control and those 3 other tank classes in there, you shouldn't have too much of a problem of being hit.  In fact my problem lately is that I've been hit too little and my defensive skills are suffering.  <br>
<br>
Summary:<br>
snare/slow, haste, regen<br>
regen, mana, mana with enchanter<br>
tank no<br>
melee yes<br>
<br>
Pardon for the very long post but this is stuff I am really interested in.  I would love to hear feedback from you Lyri, or any experienced tanks who can back up or refute anything I've said.  If I'm wrong I'd like to know so I can be a better bard and stop giving bad advice to young bards <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003030><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub7.ezboard.com/uyonderwendobrayxe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yonder Wendobrayxe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Stalker of Wolves</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/7/01 7:03:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub7.ezboard.com/faegiswolvesfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> P.S. From your group layout sounds like someone needs to twink a cleric.  I think people are discovering how boring it is to be a healing class because as of late there have been an abundance of enchanters, rogues, and warriors in midlevel zones, and very few healers.  Anyhow, maybe when Patricio gets stuck at 52 waiting for white scale for my epic around Christmas time, I can start working on leveling up Teubbie R`Notteubee <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003030><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub7.ezboard.com/ulyriprayerblade.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lyri Prayerblade</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wolf</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/8/01 1:00:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub7.ezboard.com/faegiswolvesfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mid 20's group: Something to ponder</span><hr size=1> Warning!  Bard-specific blabbing ahead.  If you are not interested in such, don't read this.<br>
<br>
Yonder... thanks for the reply.  I LOVE bard geeking.  I hope my reply starts more.  I realize it's in the worst possible form to ask for suggestions than criticize those you get, but I'm going to do exactly that in the hopes that I learn something.  Feel free to /bonk and correct me.<br>
<br>
First, in a tankish group without an enchanter, I would always always twist in haste.  No brainer.  My musing about what to sing stems from the fact that we've been grouping with an enchanter who is far better at hasting tanks than I am.  Since Anthem and Melodic Binding are voice songs, I would be using weapons and in there swinging away.  I totally agree with your suggestion in the we-have-no-enchanter case.<br>
<br>
But what about when you DO have an enchanter, plus there is a rogue in the group?  Isn't that case just a horse of another color?  With enchanter, Anthem become a cruddy strength buff only.  I can arm my weapons and sing CoB and give a better str buff plus a significant dex buff.  With no cleric, perhaps Hymn as well (taunt, Burroch! taunt), plus the snare song.  Is it so clear that the group isn't better off if I use my tambourine for CoB (giving 8 more, I think, str and dex) and lute for Hymn (almost double, I think, the regen)?  Is my bard-weapon damage better than the additional buffing I can do with instruments?  Please comment.<br>
<br>
Now, here's where I argue with your advice (forgive me, please, I know this is rude but I want to learn.)  Why would I twist in Chorus of Clarity with only a SK + Enc in the group?  If a fight takes one minute, aren't I giving them a mere 6 pulses x 6 mana= 36 mana in the course of a fight?  (Why 6 pulses?  I figure I'm not hitting them every six seconds because I'm doing some other song(s) too... I'm guesstimating.)  Is that even enough for one root?  Wouldn't that slot be better-spent with a str/dex buff or a snare/slow song?  I always just BALK at being asked to sing CoC during combat, because I really really feel I can help the party more by buffing/debuffing/healing than giving a minor mana refresh.  Feel free to correct any incorrect statements.<br>
<br>
Thanks much for the help,<br>
<br>
Harmonae &quot;But you said to get the runner!&quot; Brooksong<br>
