 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003030><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub7.ezboard.com/uyonderwendobrayxe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yonder Wendobrayxe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Stalker of Wolves</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/8/01 3:59:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub7.ezboard.com/faegiswolvesfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Mid 20's group: Something to ponder</span><hr size=1> If there's one thing to know about me it's that I love an intellectual argument.  No need to apologize whatsoever.<br>
<br>
Agreed, If you are grouping with an enchanter it's a whole different game.  I always love groups with enchanters and clerics, because I can just play manasong and take a nap =P.  Enchanter debuffs are better than bards.  Enchanter buffs are better than bards.  So enchanter slows, weakens, and pretty much puts the creature out of melee commission, handles crowd control, and hastes your tanks.  So what do you do?<br>
<br>
I should point out a couple of things.  As per the post that was recently bumped to the top of the Drinal Aegis Wolves board where Teir scares us all by telling us melee damage formulas, the extra 13 strength you provide your group by wielding a tambourine as opposed to wielding your weapons, if we are generous, will increase the MAX hit of your tank's weapons by a whopping... brace yourself... 2 damage.  Here's the math:<br>
I'm going to assume a level 27 tank with strength of 135 (probably average at your level for human tank types), maxed out offense and defense skills, and a 10 damage weapon.  Your results may vary.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
LevelBonus = (level -25)/3<br>
(Only applies to lvl 20+. If you are lower than level 20, LevelBonus = 0)<br>
<br>
Main Hand Damage<br>
-------------------------------<br>
MIN Main Hand = 1 + LevelBonus <br>
MODAL Main Hand = 2*WeaponDamage + LevelBonus <br>
MAX Main Hand = ((STR + Weaponskill)/100)*weapondamage + LevelBonus <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Level bonus = 1 (I would suppose they round up)<br>
MIN: has nothing to do with STR<br>
MODAL: has nothing to do with STR (apparently Teir is too good for the word &quot;average&quot; and has to make us think)<br>
MAX: ((125+140)/100)*10  + 1 without strength buff<br>
This totals 27 damage for a maximum hit<br>
MAX: ((138+140)/100)*10 + 1 with strength buff<br>
This totals 29 damage for a maximum hit.<br>
<br>
Now does this extra 2 points of damage once in a while (once every 20 rounds for a max hit?) worth not being in the fray, swinging your weapons for an average of maybe 10 each round?  Heck, if those numbers are right, is it even worth the effort of juggling instruments?<br>
<br>
I can't speak about dex because I don't have any good numbers.  From what I know it increases chance to hit, melee skill increases, and chance to proc.  I'm assuming you guys aren't too proc reliant nor is anyone trying to skill up a melee weapon fast, so the only reason you'd want this for regular tanks is for the increased chance to hit.  Honestly I don't have any numbers on this period.  From observation, though, chance to hit seems to be based a lot more on level relative to the creature and weapon skill rather than dex.  My bard went from having twinked out dex to having twinked out charisma, dropping dex maybe a dozen points and I never noticed a difference.<br>
<br>
Arguably the best thing that song provides is 6ac with tambourine, 3 without.<br>
<br>
I conveniently left out the part about the rogues because I honestly know next to nothing about rogues and how their backstab is calculated.<br>
<br>
You have to budget your enchanter's mana pool, but as far as the snare, our debuffs will stack with enchanters insofar as they are on the creature at the same time; however, the slow percentage doesn't stack so the only reason to use this song is to snare, and the only time you need to snare is for one or two pulses right before a creature dies (when your tanks aren't being hit anyhow).  Whenever I can get someone else to slow for a while it is wonderful because that song is resisted a lot and each resist is one less song you have in effect at any given time.  Depending on the creature, if I'm playing this song I usually can only twist two songs in combat to ensure it doesn't wear off.  Slowing a creature is one of the most important things a group can have, so it kind of stinks that the resisted song is the vital one.  Anyhow that was tangent, bottom line is I would let the enchanter slow if he/she has the mana capacity and use our slow for snaring.<br>
<br>
Now the all important hymn.  We both probably agree that it is a must.  The question is whether to use a lute or not.  The difference at level 27 is 5 points a tick without lute, 9 points with lute.  I'm not sure if sitting/standing makes a difference, but it usually does with regen.  I suppose it really depends on the group.  In a 20 tick fight, it sums to 80 points of healing.  How much are your tanks getting hit?  Can mend or life taps compensate for the lack of healing?  This one probably is a trial and error type thing.  The never ending druidic question of nuke or heal?  On one hand you dish out some damage and the creature dies faster, but on the other you give your party members more health but they get hit longer.  I say it's probably a toss up that could lean slightly in favor of just sitting back, but probably almost unnoticably.  Please test this and let me know what you find.<br>
<br>
There are selfish reasons to want to be in the fray though.  Keeping weapon skills up, and keeping up defense are 2 of them.  Patricio is about 2 levels behind in defensive skills because he doesn't get hit enough.  I can't imagine what it would be like if I sat back through fights for several levels.  Defense increases your AC and thus decreases the amount you need to be healed.  It's nice to get that occasional stray hit that bumps your AC up 4 points.<br>
<br>
As a bard I feel my damage output is pretty good.  To compensate for lack of double attack, I can haste myself and my party.  30% haste is probably as good or better than a warrior with the same weapons and skills who has double attack but no haste (or 10% before 36).  I hit pretty consistently in the upper 20s when I hit.  Helps to have a 110dd proc also.  I proced 4 times in a fight yesterday for full each time.  I ended up doing well over 500 damage that fight.  Granted I average probably 2 procs per fight, which often are partially resisted.  My damage output isn't bad.  Verant claims it should be over half what a warrior can do, which is worth being in the fray in my book.  Again, though, it all depends on the situation.  In your current situation you may need to step back.  Yesterday I was in such a group.  Our main tank was a high elf pally with way less AC than me, we had a shaman, and our healer was a druid.  We managed to end every fight near full mana and full heath because all i did was step back and twist cantata,clarity,clarity.  I say if your group facilitates your meleeing you should go for it.  Provided you aren't inconveniencing anyone else by more than a tick or two of downtime.<br>
<br>
Now, final issue (finally <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ), manasong.  Probably the single most annoyingly useful effect in the game: a couple points of instant mana infusion.  No duration, thus no icon, thus lots of whining from casters for me to play it when I've been playing it all along.  I was tempted to name myself Patricio I`Malreadyfrickinplayingmanasong.  I spent 51 levels as a druid and I think the power of a couple of points of mana is vastly underestimated by bards and tanks alike.  According to a post on castersrealm, breeze adds 2 points of mana ever 6 seconds or so.  Those numbers may be off but I've heard numerous people say that bard breeze is better than breeze or possibly on par with clarity if played nonstop so I'm inclined to believe that number.  Which means that 2 points of mana you are adding every 3 ticks is like making breeze give 66% more mana.  In one fight it doesn't matter, but in the end it adds up a lot.  It means the enchanter can do more and can go oom less, and have a higher mana level overall.  That 36 mana a fight you cited for a level 27 enchanter is almost a 6 second stun or a melee debuff, and much more than a magic resist debuff of appropriate level.  If one thing has to leave my twist for a tick or two it is usually manasong because it doesn't have that much direct impact on the current fight, but over the long haul I guarantee it works wonders.<br>
<br>
So for this situation, I would personally do regen, mana, mana, skipping a mana for snare when it's time for the creature to start running.  On the weapon issue I'd like to hear some empirical observations and maybe even see some log parsing data if you are feeling especially bard geeky.  I'm quite curious.<br>
